        <p class="pg-eyebrow">January</p>
        <h1 class="pg-title">Janus</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Roman two-faced god of doorways, beginnings, and transitions</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        The month of January on the Gregorian calendar honors a Roman god whose worship was woven into the fabric of Roman daily life. His name was <strong>Janus</strong>, and he was the god of doorways, transitions, and beginnings — depicted with two faces, one looking backward and one looking forward.
      </p>

      <h2>Who He Was</h2>

      <p>
        Janus was unique even among Roman gods. He had no Greek equivalent — he was Rome's own creation, one of the oldest deities in their pantheon. He was the god of <em>beginnings</em>: every doorway, every threshold, every passage from one state to another belonged to him. Romans invoked him at the start of every important act — a marriage, a journey, a sacrifice, a war. Even when sacrificing to other gods, the Romans named Janus first.
      </p>

      <p>
        His most famous symbol was his two faces — one looking into the past, one looking into the future. He stood at every threshold as the gatekeeper between what was and what would be. His temple in Rome had doors that were left open in time of war and closed only in time of peace, so that Janus might travel out with the legions. The first month of the Roman year was dedicated to him because January marked the doorway from one year to the next. Latin <em>Ianuarius</em> became January.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        The pagan world wanted a god of beginnings — someone to bless the transition from one chapter of life to the next, to guard the doorways and oversee the journeys. Yahuah's people need no such god. He is the one who blesses comings in and goings out, who opens doors and closes them, who walks with His people from the start of every chapter to the end of it.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Psalm 121:8</span> — "Yahuah shall preserve thy going out and thy coming in from this time forth, and even for evermore."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Deuteronomy 28:6</span> — "Blessed shalt thou be when thou comest in, and blessed shalt thou be when thou goest out."
      </div>

      <p>
        Yahuah Himself stands at the doorways of His people's lives. He needs no Janus to keep watch. Naming a month after a two-faced god of transitions credits a creature with what only the Creator does — and the creature in question never existed in the first place.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        Some will ask: <em>"What month in Yahuah's calendar is January really?"</em> The question itself is the mistake.
      </p>

      <p>
        Yahuah's months are counted from the new moon. The first month — Aviv — begins when Spica meets the moon at the new moon nearest the spring equinox. Every month after that begins the day after the visible new-moon sliver appears. The months are numbered: Aviv, Month 2, Month 3, and so on, through Month 12 or Month 13 depending on the year. <strong>Their start dates do not line up with the Roman months — and they shift slightly from one year to the next, because the heavens are the timekeeper, not a printed calendar.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        What we call "January" on the Roman calendar will overlap with parts of two different months on Yahuah's calendar — and which two depends on the year. To say "January is really Month X" is to commit the same error as saying "Christ died on Friday." It mixes Babylon's clock with Yahuah's clock, when the two were never meant to translate into each other.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        The month believers most associate with "new beginnings" — the month of resolutions, of fresh starts, of looking forward and looking back — is named after a god of transitions whom the Romans invented. Even the cultural feel of January, as a doorway between years, is borrowed Janus-language carried forward into the modern world. Most who say "January" have no idea. But the name was put there deliberately, by people who bowed to a two-faced god.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> His months are counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from a Roman god of doorways. The faithful watch the heavens and let the new moon tell them when a month has begun. The world watches its phone and lets Janus tell it the year has turned. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        January is Janus's month. The doorways of His people's lives are kept by Yahuah Himself — not by a two-faced god the Romans invented to mark their thresholds.
      </div>

